<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHILDREN IN LAS VEGAS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 "Las Vegas Gambles on Families," Sept. 23, regarding the problem of children 
in Las Vegas casinos, doesn't address the reason for the problem. Despite 
grumblings to the contrary, many of the casino owners are shrewdly cultivating 
their own future clientele. 
</P>
<P>
 Twenty years from now the kid with the dirty diaper on the floor of the MGM 
Grand will be back at the Grand playing the slots and the tables. After a 
number of visits in his younger years he will have become used to the 
environment and he'll see that Las Vegas is fun. It's a self-perpetuating 
system. Vegas owners are conditioning parents to bring their children to Las 
Vegas for a good time. As soon as the kid becomes 21 he becomes a customer on 
his own. It's like a pyramid. 
</P>
<P>
 ROBERT E. THOMPSON 
</P>
<P>
 Sylmar 
</P>
