<HEADLINE>
<P>
POLITICAL PRACTICES COMMISSION REJECTS FINE THAT STAFF URGED FOR SEN. CALDERON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From a Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The state Fair Political Practices Commission on Thursday rejected a staff 
recommendation to fine state Sen. Charles Calderon (D-Whittier) $15,000 for 
using campaign funds for such personal items such as tennis clothes. 
</P>
<P>
 During a brief debate, Commissioner Deborah Seiler characterized the proposed 
fine as "too heavy a hit" and said she favored a penalty of $6,000 to $10,000. 
</P>
<P>
 The commission staff determined that Calderon had improperly dipped into his 
campaign funds to pay for tennis gear, entertainment for his son's birthday 
party and his wife's modeling photographs. 
</P>
<P>
 In a stipulated agreement signed last month, Calderon, who is seeking 
reelection, agreed to pay the $15,000 fine stemming from an investigation by 
the watchdog agency. 
</P>
<P>
 But on a 3-2 vote, the commission turned down the settlement deal and sent the 
dispute back to its staff for more negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
