<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: DANA POINT; HIGH-RISE GARAGE WILL BOW TO CITY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF BEAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Capistrano Beach man will remove a half-completed third-story addition to 
his garage as part of an agreement with the city. 
</P>
<P>
 In late June, the city mistakenly gave Gary Geisel building permits for his 
project, which added second and third floors to his garage. 
</P>
<P>
 But when a neighbor complained after work began, city officials took another 
look, discovered their zoning blunder and halted construction. 
</P>
<P>
 As part of a compromise worked out between Geisel and the city, the Planning 
Commission on Wednesday approved a zoning variance that allows a second-story 
addition to the garage. Such a project would normally be prohibited because of 
setback requirements for that structure. Many of the homes in the neighborhood, 
however, have two-story structures. 
</P>
<P>
 Geisel said Thursday that he was unsure how much time and material had gone 
into the third story. He did the job himself and said he cannot reuse the 
lumber that he must tear down. 
</P>
<P>
 Geisel said he is negotiating a compensation settlement with the city. 
</P>
<P>
 "As hard as it's been, I've got to give the city credit for working with me," 
Geisel said. 
</P>
<P>
 Geisel's wife, Donna, said she is anxious to put the incident behind. 
</P>
<P>
 The couple plan to build a second story to their house that will connect with 
the addition on the garage. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's not what we originally planned, but it will turn out better," Donna 
Geisel said. 
</P>
<P>
 Some neighbors are certain to be pleased. Two months ago, one neighbor likened 
the original three-story structure to putting a skyscraper in downtown Dana 
Point.JEFF BEAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
