<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: LOS ANGELES COUNTY; 
SUPERVISORS TENTATIVELY OK LIMIT ON GARAGE SALES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Board of Supervisors moved Thursday to tighten restrictions on what for 
some Southern Californians has become a weekend habit, tentatively approving an 
ordinance to limit garage and yard sales in unincorporated areas to twice a 
year. 
</P>
<P>
 "This was spurred by a number of complaints about people conducting these 
sales on a weekend basis, some of them even selling new merchandise and 
essentially doing business in a residential area," said Robert Alaniz, a 
spokesman for Supervisor Gloria Molina, who sponsored the measure."These are 
not the typical 'let's clean out the garage and closet' types." 
</P>
<P>
 The ordinance allows residents to have two garage sales a year, with each sale 
not to exceed three consecutive days. Sale hours would be limited from 7 a.m. 
till 6 p.m. and signs advertising the sale would be limited to one for each 
street surrounding a residence. 
</P>
<P>
 The ordinance was tentatively approved on a 3-1 vote, with Supervisor Mike 
Antonovich dissenting. 
</P>
<P>
 A vote on final approval of the ordinance is scheduled in two weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
